              h: "Anchoring: The First Number Wins",
              body: "Anchoring is among the most replicated effects in behavioral economics: the first number a buyer sees becomes the reference point against which everything after is judged — even when the anchor is arbitrary.\n\nApplications, from crude to elegant:\n\n- **Crossed-out pricing** ('$497 → $297') — works, but reads as discount-brand; use sparingly and only truthfully.\n- **Cost-of-alternative anchoring** — before your price appears, establish what solving this otherwise costs: the $3k/month agency, the $15k mistake, the year of stalled growth. Your $997 now lands downhill.\n- **Value-stack anchoring** — itemized component values totaling far above the ask (keep the itemization honest and defensible).\n- **Premium-first sequencing** — on calls and pages, present the top tier first. Whatever follows feels lighter, and some buyers simply take the anchor.\n\nThe meta-rule: never let your price be the first number in the conversation. Build the frame; then name the figure inside it."
