              body: "$97 and $100 are three dollars apart in revenue and a world apart in signal. Charm pricing — endings in 7 and 9 — pattern-matches to deals and direct response; research on left-digit perception supports a real conversion bump in value-oriented markets. Prestige pricing — clean round numbers, $1,000, $5,000 — pattern-matches to confidence and luxury: 'this is the price; it needs no psychological garnish.'\n\nThe choice is brand congruence, not superstition. A $2,997 luxury-positioned mastermind whispers discount-brand at odds with its own promise; a $500 impulse-priced template pack loses nothing to charm pricing. High-ticket services and premium personal brands generally price round; volume digital products generally price charm.\n\nAnnual-vs-monthly framing belongs here too: '$40/month' reads smaller than '$480/year' for the identical commitment — frame the smaller unit for entry offers, the total for prestige offers where a serious number signals a serious client. Every digit is copy. Write it deliberately."
