              h: "Guarantees: Transferring the Risk",
              body: "Every transaction carries risk, and by default the buyer holds all of it: their money, their time, their hope. A guarantee transfers some of that load to the seller — directly raising 'perceived likelihood' in the value equation.\n\nThe taxonomy, in ascending strength:\n\n- **Conditional**: refund if you did the work ('complete the modules, show your posts, and if no growth — full refund'). Filters refund-abuse, demands effort.\n- **Unconditional**: 30 days, no questions. Maximum trust signal, maximum exposure.\n- **Performance-based**: tied to an outcome ('we deliver X or work free until we do' / 'you don't pay unless the deal closes'). The strongest signal that exists — it prices your confidence.\n\nThe fear is always a refund tsunami; the direct-response record says otherwise: stronger guarantees typically raise net revenue, because the conversion lift among honest hesitators outweighs the marginal refunds. Trust the math over the fear — and never offer a guarantee on a product you privately doubt. The guarantee's real function is forcing *you* to build something guaranteed-worthy."
