              h: "The Compounding Cost of Fake Countdowns",
              body: "The evergreen countdown timer that resets on every visit is the most common lie in internet marketing — and the audience learned to check years ago. Open the page in an incognito tab, watch the timer reboot: caught.\n\nCount the real cost. A faked deadline may lift this launch a few points. But each caught lie reprices *all* your future claims: the next deadline gets discounted, then the testimonials, then the results. You trained your audience that your words carry asterisks, and audiences never fully un-learn that. For a creator whose entire model is repeat launches to the same warm audience, this is selling the orchard for one harvest of apples.\n\nThe inverse compounds just as hard. Close the cart when you said you would — publicly decline the 'can I still get in?' DMs the day after ('doors are closed; next cohort is March; want the waitlist?'). It stings once. From then on, every deadline you announce moves buyers *early*, because your audience has evidence you mean it. Kept deadlines are a brand asset with a yield."
