              body: "The testing hierarchy most advertisers get backwards: they A/B test button colors while never testing the *message*. Order of leverage, descending:\n\n1. **Angle** — the core persuasive frame: pain-led ('tired of posting into the void?'), desire-led ('imagine brands DMing you'), status-led, speed-led, contrarian ('why posting daily keeps you broke'), proof-led ('how Marta booked 3 listings'). Different angles reach *different psychological buyers* of the same product.\n2. **Hook** — the first three seconds within a winning angle.\n3. **Format** — talking head vs. UGC testimonial vs. demonstration vs. text-on-screen.\n4. **Structural elements** — length, CTA phrasing, opening frame.\n5. **Cosmetics** — thumbnails, colors, music. Test last, if ever.\n\nA new account should test three to five *angles* first, because an angle winner routinely outperforms an angle loser by multiples — while cosmetic variants move results by percents. Find the message the market votes for; only then optimize its delivery. Testing variations of an unproven angle is polishing a door nobody wants to open."
