              body: "An audience is a one-to-many broadcast: you perform, they watch, and every relationship in the room runs through you. A community is many-to-many: members know *each other*, help each other, and would lose something real by leaving — even if you went quiet for a month.\n\nThe strategic difference is where the switching costs live. An audience's exit cost is zero — one tap, unfollowed, replaced by the next creator in the feed. A community member who leaves abandons relationships, reputation, accumulated status, and inside context. That is a moat no algorithm change touches.\n\nThe economics follow: community products sustain recurring revenue (memberships, cohorts) at retention rates one-off products never see; the community generates its own content and support (members answering members — value you do not personally produce); and it is the highest-fidelity VOC source that exists, feeding every other lesson in this school.\n\nThe test of which you have: post a question and leave for a day. Silence, or replies to *you* only? Audience. Members answering members? Community. Everything in this lesson engineers the second outcome."
